# Pangolin DNS reference (generated by Terraform)
# Public IP: ${public_ip}
# When manage_vercel_dns = true, these records are created via vercel_dns_record in Terraform.
# Docs: https://docs.pangolin.net/self-host/dns-and-networking

## Wildcard (public HTTPS resources)
Type: A
Name: *
Value: ${public_ip}
TTL: 300

## Dashboard (${dashboard_host})
Type: A
Name: ${dashboard_host}
Value: ${public_ip}
TTL: 300
%{ if enable_integration_api ~}

## Integration API (${integration_api_host}) — pangolin-operator
Type: A
Name: ${integration_api_host}
Value: ${public_ip}
TTL: 300
URL: ${integration_api_url}/v1 (Swagger: ${integration_api_url}/v1/docs)
Covered by wildcard * record when vercel_wildcard_dns = true.
%{ endif ~}

## Optional root apex (only if you use the apex as a resource)
# Type: A
# Name: @  (${base_domain})
# Value: ${public_ip}

## Installer / ACME email
${letsencrypt_email}

## TLS (Traefik HTTP-01)
Traefik requests certs via HTTP on port 80. Requirements:
- Exactly ONE A record per hostname (dashboard + wildcard). Let's Encrypt checks every A; extra IPs (e.g. homelab) cause failure → browser shows "TRAEFIK DEFAULT CERT".
- ${public_ip} must answer on TCP 80 and 443 from the internet (OCI security list + UFW + docker compose up).
- After fixing DNS, on the VM: sudo rm -f config/letsencrypt/acme.json && sudo touch config/letsencrypt/acme.json && sudo chmod 600 config/letsencrypt/acme.json && sudo docker compose restart traefik
- Logs: sudo docker logs traefik 2>&1 | grep -iE 'acme|certificate|error'

## Tunnel endpoint hostname (set gerbil.base_endpoint to this in Pangolin config)
${tunnel_host}

## Open ports (OCI + host firewall)
TCP 22 (SSH — restrict source)
TCP 80, 443
UDP 51820 (sites / Newt)
UDP 21820 (clients)
